<td><FONT SIZE="1" FACE="Verdana, Arial" COLOR="#D0BC90">Originally posted by lynn on 08-02-2002 11:11 AM<BR></FONT>
<TEXTAREA NAME="EditedMessage" ROWS=20 COLS=75 WRAP="VIRTUAL">[URL=http://rpgvault.ign.com/articles/366/366528p1.html]RPGVault[/URL] has posted up a Divine Divinity Hands-On Preview. The article describes their impressions of the recent press build, the backstory, gameplay, NPC and item interaction, combat, user interface, graphics, and more. 

Here's a snippet: 

[i]NPC interaction is more developed than most action-oriented RPGs. Each one you meet seems to belong to a faction and has a disposition intimately related to your actions. These disposition ratings range from 0 (neutral), to 100 (admiring) and negative numbers (hostile). Each NPC may treat you differently according to your race, your actions and quests you have performed for them. Most start neutral and most monsters you meet will be as well. However, there are the exceptions and these will depend on your travels. [/i]

And their conclusion: 

[i]With close to 100 diverse skills for 6 distinct character types, thousands of monsters and hundreds of NPCs over some 20000 screens of real estate in a fully fleshed out fantasy world, Larian Studios' RPG is looking to make a big splash sometime soon in the next few months.[/i]

Read the full preview [URL=http://rpgvault.ign.com/articles/366/366528p1.html]here[/URL]

------------------
[i]They say don't judge a book by its cover, and in equal measure don't judge a game by its name[/i]</TEXTAREA>
</td></tr>
